04709nam a22005775i 9780822395058DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223950587 a10.1515/97808223950582doi  a(DE-B1597)552282  a(OCoLC)1202625308  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM753b.V33 2013eb 7aSOC0440002bisacsh04a305.8009764/42231 aValerio-Jiménez, Omar S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRiver of Hope :bForging Identity and Nation in the Rio Grande Borderlands /cOmar S. Valerio-Jiménez, Omar S. Valerio-Jiménez. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b19 photos, 10 tables, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Maps, Figures, and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Constructing Vecinos, Constructing Indios Complex Interdependence -- tChapter 2. Fragmented Communities Class and Gender Hierarchies -- tChapter 3. Opposing Forces Political Loyalty and Trade -- tChapter 4. Bandidos or Citizens? Everyday Forms of Resistance to Political and Legal Changes -- tChapter 5. Divorcées, Rancheros, and Peons Changing Class and Gender Relations -- tChapter 6. Contested Citizenship The Enduring Roles of Race and Class -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn River of Hope, Omar S. Valerio-Jiménez examines state formation, cultural change, and the construction of identity in the lower Rio Grande region during the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. He chronicles a history of violence resulting from multiple conquests, of resistance and accommodation to state power, and of changing ethnic and political identities. The redrawing of borders neither began nor ended the region's long history of unequal power relations. Nor did it lead residents to adopt singular colonial or national identities. Instead, their regionalism, transnational cultural practices, and kinship ties subverted state attempts to control and divide the population.Diverse influences transformed the borderlands as Spain, Mexico, and the United States competed for control of the region. Indian slaves joined Spanish society; Mexicans allied with Indians to defend river communities; Anglo Americans and Mexicans intermarried and collaborated; and women sued to confront spousal abuse and to secure divorces. Drawn into multiple conflicts along the border, Mexican nationals and Mexican Texans (tejanos) took advantage of their transnational social relations and ambiguous citizenship to escape criminal prosecution, secure political refuge, and obtain economic opportunities. To confront the racialization of their cultural practices and their increasing criminalization, tejanos claimed citizenship rights within the United States and, in the process, created a new identity.Published in cooperation with the William P. Clements Center for Southwest Studies, Southern Methodist University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCitizenshipxPolitical aspectszMexico. 0aCitizenshipxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aGroup identityzMexican-American Border Region. 0aGroup identityzTexaszLower Rio Grande Valley. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh1 aValerio-Jiménez, Omar S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395058zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395058423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395058.jpg  